gep.model

Class Gene<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • gep.model.Gene<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - The return type of a node in the encoded expression tree (=the type of gene elements).
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable

    public class Gene<T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable
    This class represents a gene in gene expression programming.

    Johannes Wortmann

    • Method Detail

      • copyFrom

        public void copyFrom(Gene<T> other)
        Copies the sequence from the given other Gene into this one. This requires that both Genes share the exact same architecture.
        Parameters:
        other - The Gene from which the sequence should be copied.

      • isPartOfHead

        public boolean isPartOfHead(int idx)
        Returns true if the given index belong to the head of the gene's sequence. This function assumes that all passed indices are greater or equal to zero.
        Parameters:
        idx - The index to be checked (>= 0)
        Returns:
        True, if idx is art of the head. False, otherwise.

      • express

        public ExpressionTreeNode<T> express(Chromosome<T> chromosome)
        Creates the ExpressionTree which is encoded by the current configuration of this gene. The ExpressionTree will only contain those gene elements which are in the coding region of the Gene.
        Parameters:
        chromosome - The chromosome that contains the gene that is expressed by this expression tree.
        Returns:
        The ExpressionTree encoded by this Gene in its current configuration.

      • sequenceAt

        public GeneElement<T> sequenceAt(int idx)
        Returns the element in the sequence at the given index
        Parameters:
        idx - The elements index
        Returns:
        The element at the given index

      • getSubsequence

        public GeneElement<T>[] getSubsequence(int startIdx,
                                       int length)
        Returns the subsequence specified by the parameters as a shallow copy
        Parameters:
        startIdx - The start index of the subsequence
        length - The length of the subsequence
        Returns:
        The subsequence as a shallow copy
        Throws:
        java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException - - if copying would cause access of data outside array bounds.

      • setSequenceAt

        public void setSequenceAt(int idx,
                          GeneElement<T> newElement)
        Sets the element in the sequence at the given index to the given element.

        The given new element has to be part of the the possible elements in the genes architecture. Because of performance reasons it is not checked at runtime.

        Parameters:
        idx - The elements index
        newElement - The element that should be set a the specified index (has to be part of the architectures possible elements!)

      • setSequenceIntervall

        public void setSequenceIntervall(int pos,
                                 GeneElement<T>[] src,
                                 int srcPos,
                                 int length)
        Sets the sequence of this gene from pos to pos+length to the values given in the src array from srcPos to srcPos+length.

        The given new elements have to be part of the the possible elements in the genes architecture. Because of performance reasons it is not checked at runtime.

        Parameters:
        pos - The start position in the sequence
        src - The array from which the values should be copied
        srcPos - The start position in the source array
        length - The number of elements to be copied by the method

      • getSequenceLength

        public int getSequenceLength()
        Returns the length of the genetic sequence (length = length of head + length of tail). Thus, the length includes non-coding regions of the gene.
        Returns:
        The length of the genes sequence.

      • invalidateExpressionTreeCache

        public void invalidateExpressionTreeCache()
        Invalidates the cache holding the latest expression tree. This will make sure that the stored reference to the latest ExpressionTree will be deleted and a new one will be created when express() is called.
